So let me ask you the first question.

35
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Where do you remember getting the extraordinary laugh, which is one of the first things that people ask me about when they say that I, when they find out that I know you, is where did his laugh come from?

36
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:57,000
My mother, she told me never to hold back all this.

37
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
If I have to sneeze, sneeze.

38
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
If you have to laugh, laugh. Don't hold it back.

39
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
She says, good for your health.

40
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Oh, that's good.

41
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
Well, you followed that advice.

42
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:16,000
When we were working years ago, we, Bill and I have a history of doing a book together about his life.

43
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
I talked an awful lot about your mother.

44
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
She died long before then.

45
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I never met her.

46
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:24,000
But I didn't know your father, Mr. Charlie.

47
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:32,000
And it seemed to me in discussing and getting to know you that an awful lot of your character comes from those family people.

48
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:43,000
I think the first thing, the most memorable line you ever spoke to me was that you thought your character was formed by the fact that you never had a doubt that both of your parents loved you.

49
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Is that correct?

50
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
That's the first thing I can remember as a person.

51
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Is that, you know, or you, a baby, then the world opens up to you.

52
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
Well, I always had the confidence that my mother followed up with me.

53
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:11,000
And what they taught me was, is that if they loved me, I must be okay.

54
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So if other people encounter me and they have a problem with me, my father said, that's their little red wagon.

55
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:33,000
And so, I never worked to be liked.

56
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
Because there would be hypocritical to me.

57
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:45,000
If I wanted to do things to make somebody like me, what is it worth?

58
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:53,000
A little background you grew up in Louisiana, born in 1934 in Monroe, Louisiana.

59
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The second son of Katie and Mr. Charlie Russell.

60
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
The other figure that we talked about a lot in your childhood was your grandfather.

61
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Well, both your grandfathers, but primarily grandfather Russell, you call the old man.

62
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:22,000
He was an extraordinary, one time in Louisiana, the night of the Clucos Claire.

63
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:28,000
The Clucos Claire had this black guy on the woods beating him.

64
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:35,000
And you could hear him screaming and crying for mercy.

65
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,000
At least a bottle away.

66
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,000
So my grandfather heard that.

67
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
He went and got his shotgun and loaded it with bird seeds.

68
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:53,000
And he went out and shot it to the crowd about a half a dozen times.

69
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
And it dispersed the crowd.

70
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And he never went and seemed to get it just left.

71
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
And he saw my old duck, something others.

72
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:09,000
So he's picking up bird seeds for a week.

73
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And when my father was born, my grandfather realized

74
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:23,000
that there was no school for the black children.

75
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
So he decided he got to talk to the other guys.

76
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:30,000
And they got together enough money.

77
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:34,000
And they went to the Zobby yard and bought some lumber.

78
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
And they bargained and negotiated.

79
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
He got to pay for the lumber.

80
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:43,000
And we got the wagons and the mules to take the lumber to the site.

81
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:47,000
They were building a schoolhouse.

82
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:50,000
So when they got back to the lumber yard,

83
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
they picked up the lumber.

84
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
The guy, let me ask them, what you boys going to do with all this lumber?

85
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Well, one of them did the crowd said, we're going to build a schoolhouse for the kids.

86
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:06,000
He said, they don't need to know how to read the pick cotton.

87
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
In fact, I'm not going to let you do it, I'm not going to let you do a thing like that.

88
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,000
I'm not going to let you do a lumber.

89
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:16,000
So our grandfather said, okay, we're just going to give my money back.

90
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:22,000
He said, no, I'm not going to do that either.

91
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
There's no agreement that a white man has to respect

92
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
what about you black boys?

93
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:38,000
So my grandfather said, oh, let me get to the straight.

94
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
You're not going to give us a lumber.

95
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,000
And you're not going to give us a money back.

96
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Well, the third option is I'll have to kill you.

97
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
And when they get a shotgun,

98
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:58,000
they kind of remember, I said, well, you know,

99
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
you guys have that lumber.

100
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:07,000
And so they built the schoolhouse.

101
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And they got together $53 to hire a teacher for a year.

102
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:18,000
So they teach at the school that this built.

103
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:24,000
And that's the kind of stuff where he says, you know,

104
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:28,000
he says you're taking that top of nobody.

105
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:36,000
And a little bit of light.

106
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:41,000
My grandfather never spent much school on one single day.

107
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:46,000
My father went to the sixth grade that he dropped out.

108
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:50,000
I did four years of University of San Francisco.

109
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:55,000
And my younger's child, my daughter graduated from Harvard Law School.

110
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:00,000
So that's the evolution of the family for my grandfather,

111
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:07,000
to my kids from low school to Harvard Law School.

112
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:12,000
But at the time you were born in 1934, your mother already,

113
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
even though your father had practically no schooling

114
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,000
and your grandfather had none, she admired it.

115
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:22,000
She valued education so much, she named your little name as Felton,

116
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
after the president of, I think, Southern University of San Francisco.

117
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
His name was Felton Clark.

118
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:33,000
And so she gave me Felton to, similar path

119
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
that I was thinking about going to college.

120
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:43,000
In fact, my mother died of kidney failure.

121
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:48,000
And she was in hospital sick and she knew she was dying.

122
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:53,000
So she called my father and said, I want you to promise me something.

123
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:57,000
That you'll send my boys to college.

124
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
And my father said he promised you.

125
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:05,000
So when she died, we took her to Louisiana to be buried.

126
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
And while I was there, she had five sisters.

127
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:14,000
And they were debating who's going to take me, who's going to take my brother.

128
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,000
And he says, that debate is no bad.

129
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I'm going to take them back to California and raise them myself.

130
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:23,000
They said, no, Mac can raise the kids.

131
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
He says, I promise my mother I will try.

132
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:35,000
So he sold his business and went to work in a foundry

133
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:40,000
for less a week than had been making a day.

134
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:45,000
And the reason he did that is because he wanted to be at the time at home.

135
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,000
Yes, he had to be home every night.

136
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:51,000
He says, you can't let kids raise themselves.

137
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:55,000
And I understood that.

138
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And I appreciated that.

139
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
I just, well, I loved him.

140
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:07,000
He was like a 75th birthday.

141
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:11,000
And we were talking and I said, you know, I love you.

142
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:14,000
He says, well, I love you too.

143
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:17,000
That was the first time I'd ever said that.

144
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
But I knew it.

145
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:30,000
I think you said at one time that when he took you and your brother back to Oklahoma.

146
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,000
You went back on the train, right?

147
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
From your mother's funeral, this is in 1946.

148
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,000
You're 12.

149
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:39,000
It's very, very unusual that a single father, a widow,

150
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:41,000
would raise his two boys.

151
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:46,000
And he said, he talked, I think you said he talked to you the whole way back

152
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,000
about how you were going to live without your mother.

153
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:57,000
And he said, you had a tremendous loss.

154
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:04,000
But you got to live the way she wanted you to live.

155
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
And she was you be educated.

156
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:17,000
And I don't know much about it, but I'll help you with whatever I can.

157
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:20,000
And he said you're going to cook and clean.

158
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Well, we had a set up where I cooked my brother wasch editions.

159
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:30,000
And then the next week he cooked and I'd wash dishes.

160
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:41,000
And there was no gourmet cook to that house.

161
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:46,000
I think I remember even earlier at one point you said that down in Louisiana,

162
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,000
you were going to come home from work.

163
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:52,000
Sometimes in the whole family would go out to play and he would carry all of you?

164
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Yes, well, he was a big straw guy, okay?

165
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Six, three, two, a hundred, twenty pounds.

166
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:07,000
And we had this huge field with tall grass like a red-and-futtle house.

167
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:10,000
And we'd go play hide and seek a new tall grass.

168
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,000
When they get to our starting point,

169
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:19,000
they'll go one arm, be on the other arm, and my brother was back,

170
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:22,000
and went full speed across that field.

171
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:27,000
And I thought he was so such a superman.

172
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
Yeah, I remember.

173
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:34,000
He was a lot of things that he'd always,

174
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:37,000
when I was playing with Celtics,

175
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:39,000
at all.

176
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
I was up in the cutchers in the Catskills.

177
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And I was back and I was talking.

178
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,000
And one of the waiters came and said,

179
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:50,000
you hear what happened to Wilt?

180
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:54,000
I said, no, you get a car wreck or something,

181
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:56,000
but he said, dry fast.

182
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:03,000
And he says, no, he just signed a contract for $100,000 a year.

183
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:08,000
That's the first time any NBA player had reached that plateau.

184
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:11,000
In fact, I think Mickey Mantle,

185
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:14,000
or Jodie Margeo,

186
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
and I think really nice,

187
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:22,000
with all the four athletes making $100,000.

188
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
So I said to Red, well, I know what I want.

189
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:26,000
He just wants that.

190
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:30,000
I said, $100,000 and $1.

191
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:34,000
Because I just want to be peeing this league.

192
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
Okay?

193
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,000
So he said,

194
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
okay.

195
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,000
So I go back to my room, I call my father up,

196
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:47,000
and I said, Dad, you won't believe this.

197
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:52,000
They're going to pay me $100,000 a year to do this.

198
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:55,000
Tell you the reason I called you, tell you now,

199
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,000
you don't have to work anymore.

200
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:03,000
I'll make enough that I can think you're in the rest of the way.

201
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:06,000
He says, I don't want your damn money.

202
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:09,000
I got my own money.

203
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:13,000
I said, but that job you got's terrible.

204
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:16,000
He's working in a factory.

205
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:19,000
He says, listen.

206
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:24,000
I give these people $35 of the best years of my life.

207
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:29,000
Now, I'm going to give them a few of the bad ones.

208
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:35,000
That's exactly what he used to turn around.

209
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:38,000
I'd like to back up just a little bit for when you left one,

210
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,000
Role Louisiana, because as I understand it at any rate,

211
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:46,000
your family was part of what we now understand as the Great Migration,

212
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:50,000
or at least the World War II Migration.

213
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
A friend of mine wrote a book about it,

214
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
Isabelle Wilkerson, the wife of other sons.

215
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,000
I've met him maybe.

216
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:59,000
He's a wonderful writer.

217
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:05,000
Anyway, before your mother's funeral,

218
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:09,000
he left Louisiana and migrated first to Detroit,

219
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
and then out to Oakland.

220
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,000
Could you tell us exactly how that happened and why it happened?

221
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:22,000
Well, he first, he's working in his back factory.

222
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,000
And the S4 race.

223
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:30,000
And the boss says, can't give you a race, Charlie.

224
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:33,000
If I give you a race, you'd be making as much as some of the white bullets.

225
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,000
And I can't pay more U.S. as much as I pay the white guys.

226
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:42,000
And he used the inward to my father.

227
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,000
Just like it was nothing.

228
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,000
And so my father was at home that night.

229
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,000
And he was talking out loud.

230
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And he says, you know, I'm going to have to leave here.

231
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:01,000
Of course, if I stay here, who will raise my kids?

232
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:06,000
And they said, well, you could raise them.

233
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:07,000
He said, no.

234
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:12,000
If I stay here, either I'll kill one of them,

235
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:15,000
or one of them will kill me.

236
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:20,000
And either way, they'll be doing better to raise my kids.

237
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:28,000
So we still working on going to Detroit.

238
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:30,000
And the Ford Motor Company was hiring.

239
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:34,000
Anybody that showed up on the war tab?

240
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:38,000
This is going to be on the war too.

241
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:40,000
Yes.

242
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:44,000
So we made the arrangements to go to Detroit.

243
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:49,000
Well, Saturday, a new time was paid day at the factory.

244
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:55,000
And he says to the boss, oh, well, this is my last day.

245
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:56,000
What do you mean?

246
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:57,000
Well, I'm not coming back.

247
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:58,000
This is it.

248
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:02,000
That's after you got to check.

249
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,000
So you got to say, Charlie, if you were about that race,

250
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,000
I'll tell you why.

251
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:11,000
You just put it long in two more hours.

252
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:16,000
And that would be a really, you have to do the work just long in.

253
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,000
I'm a father, no, this is it.

254
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:24,000
See, they've got thought he was upset about the race.

255
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:30,000
But he's upset about the boss sending in word to him to his face.

256
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:31,000
Right.

257
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And that wasn't the only incident like that.

258
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Right.

259
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:37,000
That kind of stuff happened all the time.

260
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:40,000
I remember you told one about the gas station once where the...

261
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:41,000
Yes.

262
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:44,000
...I just pumped other people's gas and the rest of them sitting there.

263
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:50,000
Well, my father thought that he was being totally disrespected all the time.

264
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:57,000
So, when he told the guys, leave it, there's no time.

265
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:02,000
At six o'clock to Saturday, he got a train to Little Rock.

266
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:03,000
Okay.

267
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:07,000
He did for Detroit.

268
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:13,000
He had a Monday morning, this guy shows up at our house looking for him.

269
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:16,000
He was from the draft boy.

270
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:20,000
And he'd go tell my father if he didn't come back to work,

271
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:24,000
he'd be drafting to the army.

272
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:28,000
But he was not eligible because he had wife and two kids.

273
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:34,000
And they weren't drafting those guys like what they didn't care about that.

274
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:40,000
So, I think my father had a little way back.

275
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:43,000
But we went to him, my mother's children.

276
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:46,000
Okay, with the reports for justice.

277
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
We're rolling again.

278
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:53,000
All right, Bill, let's pick up again with the move out of Louisiana.

279
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Your father decided he couldn't stay there.

280
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:00,000
This is at the beginning of World War II and he moved first to Detroit.

281
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
And then from there to Oakland,

282
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:06,000
and he sent for the family from Oakland.

283
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,000
Is that right?

284
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:09,000
Yeah.

285
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Well, if you've ever been Detroit in the wintertime,

286
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:18,000
he said that was killing him, it was too cold.

287
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:21,000
So, he moved to Oakland, California,

288
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:27,000
and went to work in Shippewarts.

289
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:30,000
And he worked in Shippewarts until the war was over.

290
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:36,000
And then they closed the Shippewarts and did everything stopped, everything.

291
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:40,000
So, he got an idea, he bought himself a truck.

292
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:48,000
It sure got out to the belly, which was 45-hour away.

293
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:54,000
And so, talking to the farmers about getting fruit pickers.

294
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:57,000
And he made quite a business out of it.

295
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:04,000
And so, from the time I was after we went back from my mother's children

296
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:12,000
until I got to college, I always bought my school clothes, picking fruit.

297
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:19,000
And I was so proud of how much money I could make.

298
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:22,000
It wasn't even money, but it was up to whatever I could make.

299
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:31,000
And so, did I enroll in the university?

300
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:35,000
You know, it was really funny about that.

301
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:40,000
When I was in Louisiana, my mother kept me away from white people,

302
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,000
which was good.

303
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:47,000
And she kept white people away from me, because she said,

304
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:49,000
you don't know what they'll do.

305
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,000
Okay.

306
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And so, well, first of all, the California and Winter School were some white kids.

307
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:05,000
But then by the time I got to high school, it was an all-black school, except for the faculty.

308
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:12,000
And then, I went to university, and there were nine black kids on the campus

309
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:16,000
of a whole student body, and jumped back into that.

310
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:21,000
And you might say cultural shock.

311
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:37,000
But I had a pretty good career, and I was self-taught, how to play.

312
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:46,000
And the reason I say that is, I got cut from the university in the levels of grade.

313
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:56,000
And so, when I was absorbing this, the varsity coach, who had been my home room teacher in junior high school,

314
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:59,000
said, to me, I'm glad you got cut.

315
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:01,000
Why?

316
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:02,000
Or you glad?

317
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:06,000
He said, it's because of the day you can come out for the varsity.

318
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:09,000
I said, I just got cut from junior varsity.

319
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:17,000
He said, you're not, I'm not a junior varsity coach, I'm a varsity coach.

320
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:20,000
So, I'm on the varsity.

321
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:25,000
And he said, I want you to wait up to practice, to first practice.

322
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,000
I said, what is it?

323
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:28,000
What?

324
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:29,000
He said, let's go.

325
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:35,000
He took, got his car, and drove us to the boys' club.

326
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:46,000
And then he took $2, I was pocket, and bought me a year's membership.

327
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:53,000
It said, after practice here, I want you to go to the boys' club and play basketball every day.

328
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:57,000
And so, that's what I did, and that's why I learned to play.

329
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And so, I had a good fortune of not being influenced by a coach.

330
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:15,000
And so, could you hold up for a second?

331
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:17,000
Sure.

332
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:28,000
I was a varsity, all the cliché things that a coach basketball player does, I didn't do any of them.

333
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:32,000
So, they figured I couldn't play.

334
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:41,000
So, they did my whole first year, they considered that a waste of scholarship.

335
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:48,000
And so, my sophomore year, they did not renew my scholarship.

336
00:23:48,000 --> 00:24:01,000
With the coach, Augustus Peter Guilty, he went to the dean of College of Business Administration

337
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:04,000
and found an unused scholarship.

338
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:11,000
So, I played my sophomore year, a academic scholarship.

339
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:29,000
And so, my career, my sophomore year, there were a couple of things that made it interesting.

340
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:37,000
Four of the top six players on the varsity, my sophomore year, told the coach

341
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:44,000
that they did not appreciate him making him have to play with black guys.

342
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:48,000
Now, he never told me that until I had retired from Celtics.

343
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:53,000
But I know I didn't get alone with these guys.

344
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:58,000
And a lot of things happened.

345
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:02,000
I just sit as part of life.

346
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:14,000
And my first varsity gate, sent a toll of my relationship with the coach.

347
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:18,000
We played Cal Berkeley.

348
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:29,000
And the center was a preseason All-American.

349
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:35,000
The game starts and the first five shots he took, five shots he took, I blocked.

350
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:39,000
And nobody had built it, never seen anything like that.

351
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:44,000
So, they called TABOUT to discuss it.

352
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:49,000
What it was I was doing, because they didn't know what I was doing.

353
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:51,000
So, we're getting out of the huddle.

354
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:54,000
And my coach says, you can't play defense like that.

355
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:55,000
What?

356
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:57,000
I just stopped in five times a row.

357
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:59,000
It's not the way to play defense.

358
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:08,000
So, he showed me on the side of my ass saying, well, I ain't want me to play defense.

359
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,000
So, I'll go back on that track.

360
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:15,000
And the guy shoots lay up three times in a row.

361
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:20,000
And I said, this does not make sense.

362
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:25,000
So, I went back to playing the way I knew how.

363
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,000
He was really insulted by that.

364
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,000
He was trying to help me.

365
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:33,000
And I was hard-headed and stubborn.

366
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:35,000
And didn't know what I was doing.

367
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:38,000
He was trying to help me pick out what I was doing.

368
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:41,000
And I rejected.

369
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:46,000
So, he never liked me as a player from then on.

370
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:51,000
We're talking about the beginning of your basketball career at the University of San Francisco.

371
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:52,000
Right.

372
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:53,000
52 to 56.

373
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:56,000
Basketball was taught differently then.

374
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:00,000
I mean, some of the things that people now wouldn't be familiar with,

375
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:02,000
you weren't supposed to leave your feet.

376
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:07,000
Yeah, no good defensive player ever leaves his feet.

377
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:17,000
Well, basically, what I was doing in retrospect was bringing the vertical game to the game

378
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
that had been in the horror-subtle.

379
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:23,000
And this is all the good and new elements.

380
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:28,000
Seeing a high jump, which I had participated in track appeal,

381
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:32,000
I can jump over my head.

382
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:39,000
Well, in basketball and Jim, we should do exercise where we take chalk

383
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:46,000
and put it on your finger and run and jump as high and put a chalk mark.

384
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:50,000
Well, I can put a chalk mark 13 feet above the floor,

385
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:54,000
which is the top of the backboard.

386
00:27:54,000 --> 00:28:02,000
And that was going to waste.

387
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:10,000
So for three years, this coach did not like me.

388
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:18,000
But I mean about mine, that I was going to see how good I could be.

389
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:22,000
So I really worked at the BELP and the game

390
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:27,000
and part of my game was logistics.

391
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:37,000
So I learned to cover great distances in a short period of time.

392
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:46,000
And so I developed how to play.

393
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:50,000
Well, he never agreed with that.

394
00:28:50,000 --> 00:29:00,000
Although, by junior senior year, we won 55 straight games.

395
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:02,000
Which is not bad.

396
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:04,000
It was a record at the time.

397
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:08,000
And we also won back-to-back Final Fours.

398
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:15,000
And I said a record that still stands today.

399
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:24,000
In 2013, I had 27 rebounds in the championship game.

400
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:27,000
And there's still a record.

401
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
And I had 50 rebounds into two games.

402
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
The semifinals and finals.

403
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,000
But there's still a record.

404
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:43,000
But my coach was kind of a purest.

405
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:47,000
This is the way the game was supposed to be played.

406
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:49,000
And I wasn't doing that.

407
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:56,000
Some of this, you once said that even before you got to the University of San Francisco

408
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:04,000
that a lot of your skills in basketball came from mental games

409
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:07,000
that you were drawing.

410
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:12,000
You had drawn out of a library and imagining things in art

411
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
and on a trip to Northwestern.

412
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:24,000
At that time, I had the ability to use my imagination.

413
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:30,000
And so I wanted to strip of these really first class basketball players.

414
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:33,000
And I watched him do everything.

415
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:37,000
And I watched the total person, the footwork,

416
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,000
the head thinks, whatever.

417
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:42,000
Dribbling the whole thing.

418
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And the next day, like a shoot around,

419
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:49,000
I was trying to do these things.

420
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:56,000
And so, as I told one of the guys in Oakland,

421
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:00,000
he said, what about San Francisco?

422
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
I said, well, the best way to explain this,

423
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:09,000
is always what I was going to be when I got there.

424
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:18,000
You know, and I told you about what we first moved into the projects.

425
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:22,000
And my mother was getting their apartment together.

426
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,000
And I was sitting on the steps and standing out the way.

427
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And these five guys ran by.

428
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:31,000
And what I'm slept is he went by.

429
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:33,000
Well, I was nine years old.

430
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:36,000
And I didn't know what nine years old was supposed to do.

431
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:40,000
I wouldn't told my mother.

432
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:43,000
And she said, what?

433
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:46,000
She grabbed a key to the house and grabbed me.

434
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:50,000
We went all through the projects looking for those five guys.

435
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And so she said, these guys, I said, yes, ma'am.

436
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:56,000
I know what she's going to do.

437
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:58,000
I thought she's going to take care of it.

438
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:00,000
But the way she took care of it was,

439
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:06,000
OK, you're going to find everyone, all five of them one at a time.

440
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:08,000
Thanks, ma'am.

441
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:13,000
So I go into five fights.

442
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:18,000
And I lose three and went to.

443
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And so we go back to our place and I'm crying.

444
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:25,000
And she says, no cry.

445
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:29,000
You did what you're supposed to do.

446
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:31,000
The matter will you want to lose.

447
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:35,000
The matter is you stood up for yourself.

448
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:39,000
And that's what you must always do.

449
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:43,000
Stand up for yourself.

450
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:50,000
And so that day, she wrote an attitude about,

451
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:57,000
she says, not a word she's ever ever pick a fight.

452
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:06,000
But always finish the fight that you end.

453
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:10,000
And so that's the kind of stuff I got my mother, my father.

454
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:14,000
And the role was almost reversed.

455
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:16,000
She told me to be a tough fighter.

456
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:21,000
And he told me to be philosophical.

457
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:23,000
Well, he was philosophical.

458
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:26,000
Yes, he was.

459
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:30,000
You know, great Taylor, I tell you how my father was.

460
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:33,000
He would never take anything from me.

461
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:34,000
I always make a lot of money.

462
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:36,000
He would never take anything.

463
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:38,000
He says, this attitude is like I got my own money.

464
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:40,000
I don't need yours.

465
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:45,000
So, for his birthday, wasn't you?

466
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:50,000
I went to a local automobile dealer and bought a car.

467
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
And told the salesman, I want you to take this car

468
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:56,000
and deliver it to this address.

469
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:58,000
And don't say anything.

470
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:00,000
The man comes to the door,

471
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:03,000
have the keys and send us your car and leave.

472
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:07,000
No explanation.

473
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:08,000
So, I'll call him up.

474
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:09,000
I said, did you get the car?

475
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:11,000
He said, yes.

476
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:13,000
I just can't believe it about there's something

477
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:15,000
that nice to put me.

478
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:18,000
I said, well, it's okay.

479
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:21,000
So, a week later, he says,

480
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:23,000
I said, okay, how you doing?

481
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:26,000
He said, oh, to kick your ass.

482
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:28,000
What?

483
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:29,000
What did I do?

484
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:32,000
He says, I just got my first speed ticket.

485
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:46,000
That's, that's San Francisco.

486
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:51,000
I think you once said 1956 was a pretty amazing year in sports.

487
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:53,000
That's your senior year.

488
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:56,000
And you were not only in the NCAA Final Four

489
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:58,000
for the second year in the row of winning it,

490
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:00,000
but you also went to the Olympics and straight into the NBA.

491
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:02,000
Right.

492
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:06,000
Well, we won the Final Four.

493
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Who did you beat?

494
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:09,000
Who did you remember?

495
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:12,000
Oh, you know, we beat Iowa.

496
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:15,000
That's what's it meant, too.

497
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:17,000
You know, we played this guys

498
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:23,000
and the guys at Iowa were first class bunch of guys.

499
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:25,000
You know, in fact, for years,

500
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:29,000
I kept up with them.

501
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:35,000
Long after we played against each other.

502
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:41,000
In fact, my counterpart, Bill Logan, who was a center,

503
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:44,000
was in Iowa Bank of the Association.

504
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:46,000
The years later, I went and spoke to him

505
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:48,000
what their conventions.

506
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:54,000
Well, anyway, I was on the Olympic team.

507
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:59,000
And in the gold medal game,

508
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:04,000
we beat the Soviet Union by 35 points.

509
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:12,000
We were kind of being guys.

510
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:14,000
See, in the tournament,

511
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:17,000
we played a team from Thailand.

512
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:19,000
Okay.

513
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:23,000
Their center is 5'10".

514
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:27,000
And so you would say,

515
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:29,000
well, these guys are all competition.

516
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:32,000
That's just walk through it.

517
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:34,000
No.

518
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:38,000
Let's find out how bad we can beat these guys.

519
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:43,000
We were going to try to beat them by 100 points.

520
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:48,000
I always think we got to be able to 80, 85.

521
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:52,000
But, uh,

522
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:54,000
I had a lot of fun.

523
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:57,000
So after the Olympics,

524
00:36:57,000 --> 00:36:59,000
I went home, got married,

525
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:02,000
and then went to Boston.

526
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:11,000
And I had not talked to the Celtics before that.

527
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:13,000
I was really an amateur.

528
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:16,000
And I got there,

529
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:21,000
and we had an idea of what was going to be.

530
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:26,000
It took about half an hour to work that out.

531
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:29,000
And so it is 13 months.

532
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:32,000
We filed for the Olympic gold.

533
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:35,000
And by rookie year, we won NBA.

534
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:38,000
So we were the college championship,

535
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:40,000
the World Amateur Championships,

536
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:43,000
and the professor championship in 13 months.

537
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And, uh, that's pretty good run.

538
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:50,000
Is it true that, um, when you went to Boston,

539
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:52,000
that Walter Brown,

540
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:54,000
the owner of the Celtics,

541
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:56,000
and Red Al back in Bill Sharman,

542
00:37:56,000 --> 00:37:58,000
that year at the airport?

543
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:00,000
Well, I think Red was on the road.

544
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:02,000
But Bill Sharman,

545
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:04,000
no, it was all three of you, right?

546
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:07,000
Red, Walter Brown, and, uh,

547
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:08,000
Bill Sharman.

548
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:09,000
Bill Sharman.

549
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:12,000
Now Walter Brown was,

550
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:16,000
one of the most marvelous people I've ever encountered.

551
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:19,000
The owner of the Celtics.

552
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:20,000
Yes.

553
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:22,000
Uh,

554
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:25,000
see there were things that the Celtics did

555
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:28,000
that, uh,

556
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:32,000
I don't think it coming knowledge.

557
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:36,000
The first black player drafted,

558
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:38,000
it did be a,

559
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:41,000
was a guy that chucked Cooper from Duques.

560
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:43,000
The Celtics drafted him.

561
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:45,000
And at the draft, uh,

562
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:48,000
one of the other owners said to Walter Brown,

563
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:51,000
you know he's colored.

564
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:52,000
And Walter Brown said,

565
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:53,000
okay, he's poking out.

566
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:56,000
That's how we drafted.

567
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:57,000
Okay.

568
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:00,000
Fast forward.

569
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:03,000
The Celtics were the first NBA team

570
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:07,000
to start five black guys.

571
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:10,000
It was an accident.

572
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:11,000
Uh, or, or,

573
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:14,000
surely how the Celtics were.

574
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:17,000
We, we were doing it for over a week.

575
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:22,000
And didn't know it until we read about the paper.

576
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:25,000
She told me Hudson was,

577
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:29,000
uh, one of the forwards and he got injured.

578
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:33,000
And so his substitute went in

579
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:36,000
and filled in until Hudson got back.

580
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And so he had five black guys start.

581
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:41,000
And, uh,

582
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:42,000
like I said,

583
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:44,000
we didn't know about until we read the paper.

584
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:46,000
Because this was the pop,

585
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:48,000
these are guys that are rotation, you know.

586
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:51,000
And so, so now you got,

587
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:52,000
first black guy signed,

588
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:57,000
first five black guys started.

589
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:01,000
We had a guy named Sam Jones

590
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:03,000
from North Carolina College,

591
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:08,000
one of quote, traditional Negro colleges.

592
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:12,000
Well, we drafted Sam in the first round.

593
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:16,000
That was the first time in any sport

594
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:19,000
that a guy from one of the Negro colleges

595
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:22,000
was drafted in the first round.

596
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:25,000
You see the difference is,

597
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:27,000
if you drafted the first round,

598
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:28,000
you're on the team,

599
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:31,000
you have to play your way off.

600
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:33,000
If you drafted in the second round,

601
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:36,000
you got to make the team.

602
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:40,000
And so your compensation is different.

603
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:47,000
So, Sam was our first pick.

604
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:51,000
It turned out to be a great, great pick.

605
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,000
And then,

606
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:57,000
the Celtics were the first team

607
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:00,000
to hire black coach.

608
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:04,000
You? Yeah.

609
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:07,000
And the way that happened was our back says to me,

610
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:10,000
I'm retiring.

611
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:14,000
And I'll have to pick the next coach.

612
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:17,000
And I will not hire anybody

613
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:24,000
that you don't want to prove of 100%.

614
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:26,000
So, he says,

615
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:28,000
what we're going to do is we're going to make,

616
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:29,000
you make a list,

617
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:32,000
and I'll make a list of five guys

618
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:34,000
that will be okay with you.

619
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:37,000
And I'll have five guys who are okay with me.

620
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:40,000
And who else is on both lists?

621
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:43,000
Is this who gets a job?

622
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:48,000
Well, there was nobody on both lists.

623
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:52,000
And so,

624
00:41:52,000 --> 00:41:54,000
Rich says,

625
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:57,000
well, I'm going to hire this one guy.

626
00:41:57,000 --> 00:41:59,000
I said, Brad, if you hire him,

627
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:02,000
I will retire with you.

628
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:04,000
Who's the guy that you think is good coach?

629
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:05,000
I said, make a difference.

630
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:09,000
I don't even want to be in the same room with him.

631
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:13,000
So, he said, well, what am I going to do?

632
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:16,000
We're going back here to offer me the job first.

633
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,000
And I said, Brad, I want you to step you in through.

634
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:22,000
No way.

635
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:24,000
And so, he said, well, what am I going to do?

636
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:25,000
I said, okay, I'll take it.

637
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:27,000
I said, here's the deal, though, Rich.

638
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:30,000
I'll take the job.

639
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:34,000
If it doesn't work,

640
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:39,000
we'll know after about an alter game.

641
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,000
And if we agree it's not working,

642
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:43,000
you can hire anybody who wants,

643
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:49,000
and I guarantee you to give them 100% cooperation.

644
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:52,000
But we never got to that.

645
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:53,000
So, that was the deal.

646
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:54,000
Yes.

647
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:55,000
That's 1966, right?

648
00:42:55,000 --> 00:42:58,000
Not only a coach, but a player coach.

649
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:02,000
What has that had there been other player coaches in the NBA?

650
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:04,000
I don't know.

651
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:05,000
You know, I...

652
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:09,000
A whole assistant coach is, I mean, people today must be shocked.

653
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:11,000
There are so many, I don't know how many assistant coaches are.

654
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:15,000
Well, Rich says, do you want to assist it?

655
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:17,000
I didn't know.

656
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:18,000
He said, why not?

657
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:24,000
I said, okay, Rich, give me what you assist us.

658
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:27,000
Well, Rich had never had an assistant.

659
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:28,000
Okay.

660
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:31,000
So, I said, why don't you have an assistant?

661
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:36,000
He's not just another guy you have to coach.

662
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:42,000
And...

663
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:47,000
Well, the atmosphere in Boston

664
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:51,000
would have been detrimental to the situation I thought

665
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:55,000
if I had a assistant coach.

666
00:43:55,000 --> 00:44:00,000
Because half a season into it, they said,

667
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:04,000
well, they had gotten to it on the coach and rushed it just to pick it up.

668
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:07,000
No better word.

669
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:11,000
Well, if I was on the coach, I wouldn't be the coach.

670
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:13,000
Okay.

671
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:18,000
And so, I should wear a dune.

672
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:28,000
And it's very interesting that Rich, last year,

673
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:35,000
as a coach, he got thrown out of 22 games,

674
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:41,000
including the All-Star Games.

675
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:46,000
And so, as a captain, I had to take the rest of the game.

676
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:49,000
So, I went in with some experience on how to do it.

677
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:53,000
And we had, as a captain,

678
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:57,000
we used to play Jim Romeo at night after games.

679
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:00,000
Because neither one was going to sleep after a game.

680
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:05,000
And we talked about coaching philosophy.

681
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:13,000
And what he wanted to do was set up a system.

682
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:16,000
Make sure that everybody knows it.

683
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:20,000
And they get the hell out of the way.

684
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:24,000
And that was the way he coached it.

685
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:28,000
And that's the way he got the team together.

686
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,000
Because I trusted him completely.

687
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:36,000
And he should do some things that I asked him about.

688
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:42,000
For example, you know, I played for Boston for 13 seasons.

689
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:48,000
And during that 13 seasons, we all have made one trade.

690
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:51,000
And we picked some guys up after they retired.

691
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:53,000
And we give them another year.

692
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:57,000
But he never said to anybody,

693
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:00,000
the way you played there,

694
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:02,000
you got to play different here.

695
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:05,000
I got you here because of the way you played there.

696
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:06,000
So, I don't want you to change.

697
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:10,000
That's the way I want you to play.

698
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:15,000
And so, guys did not have to quote the play for themselves.

699
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:20,000
They did not have to learn a new way of playing.

700
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:24,000
You got you there where you were before you got here.

701
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:28,000
And he had a place for you in that system.

702
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:33,000
Why did he get thrown out of so many games?

703
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:36,000
Why did great dollar back get thrown out of so many games?

704
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:39,000
Did it serve a purpose or was it just a personality?

705
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:43,000
A coalition.

706
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:46,000
He was never going to the sideline and said,

707
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:48,000
what the heck?

708
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:54,000
He says, my team, I can't get my team to fight for me if I won't fight for them.

709
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:57,000
In fact, my first game,

710
00:46:57,000 --> 00:46:59,000
Riffrey called Goldit-Hinti,

711
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:03,000
which was not Goldit-Hinti.

712
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:07,000
Redwood Nuts.

713
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:11,000
He got to be yelled and screamed and stopped until the Riffrey called it,

714
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:14,000
that's the melody.

715
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:20,000
But they were careful after that when they called Goldit-Hinti.

716
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:23,000
That was his purpose.

717
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:28,000
And after the game, I said to Red,

718
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:31,000
you know the first coach that's asked you,

719
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:35,000
that looked up for me.

720
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:39,000
He says,

721
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:42,000
I can't expect my players to fight for me if I won't fight for them.

722
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:44,000
That's the way I coach.

723
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:46,000
It wasn't you.

724
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:50,000
It's thanks Red.

725
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:52,000
Did you talk a little bit?

726
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:54,000
You played on the storied Celtic teams,

727
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:57,000
you won 11 championships in 13 years.

728
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:01,000
Just a little bit of personality sketches of the various players on the team,

729
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:04,000
like Sam Jones and, you know, what they were like.

730
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:07,000
Well, first of all,

731
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:10,000
more important to me

732
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:13,000
than when 11 championships.

733
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:16,000
We weren't eating a roll.

734
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:20,000
That was difficult.

735
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:24,000
You know, of course you got to do the same things

736
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:27,000
with them repeating yourself,

737
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:33,000
which takes some planning.

738
00:48:33,000 --> 00:48:38,000
Well, I played with some guys that were,

739
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:43,000
we had a family.

740
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:46,000
I liked all the guys except for two,

741
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:50,000
and they were never the who they were.

742
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:53,000
You know,

743
00:48:53,000 --> 00:49:00,000
at least two I was available about, you know,

744
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:06,000
Bill Sharman,

745
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:14,000
most thoughtful player I've played with.

746
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:17,000
He did everything about it numbers.

747
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:22,000
And we'd fight at the drop of a hat,

748
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:24,000
and we were always throwing something else around.

749
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:27,000
Some braids around.

750
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:34,000
I think Sharman led the league in fights.

751
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:41,000
A coupzy could not fight.

752
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:44,000
So what his ex-red did was very interesting.

753
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:47,000
We should play Syracuse,

754
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:50,000
and their guards used to beat up a coupzy.

755
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:52,000
Just beat him up.

756
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:54,000
Okay, that's a foul.

757
00:49:54,000 --> 00:49:58,000
We go beat him up.

758
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:00,000
So Red got so insist about that.

759
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:03,000
So one night he said, okay,

760
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:05,000
we had a guy named John Williams,

761
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:09,000
Luskatov.

762
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:11,000
Big, look how you've been lifted,

763
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:12,000
weights and all that.

764
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:15,000
He says, Luskie, listen.

765
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:18,000
I want you to watch.

